        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "Effort:"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " Small, once #4 is implemented. The inline eval renderer and the autocomplete insertion mechanism would be the same."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":h3",
        {
          "s": "10. Undo/redo for structural operations"
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "Gap:"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " Browser-native undo (Ctrl+Z) works for inline text edits within a single contentEditable element, because the browser tracks its own undo stack per element. However, structural AST operations — block splitting/merging, list indent/outdent, block type shortcut conversions, autocomplete insertions — bypass the browser’s undo stack entirely. These operations manipulate the AST directly and re-render, so Ctrl+Z either does nothing or produces inconsistent state."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "Scope:"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " Implement an AST-level undo/redo stack. Capture AST snapshots (or diffs) before each structural operation. Ctrl+Z/Ctrl+Y (or Ctrl+Shift+Z) pops the stack and re-renders from the restored AST. Must coexist with browser-native inline undo — only intercept when the browser’s own undo stack is exhausted or when the last operation was structural."
        }
      ],
      [
        ":p",
        [
          ":strong",
          {
            "s": "Effort:"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": " Medium. The snapshotting is straightforward (deep-clone AST before each "
        },
        [
          ":code",
          {
            "s": "emitChange"
          }
        ],
        {
          "s": "), but coexisting with browser-native undo and preserving cursor position across undo/redo adds complexity."
        }
